---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Section from "../components/Section.astro";
import OurRoadmap from "../components/Roadmap.astro";

const title = "Roadmap — Odal Node";
const description =
  "What is shipped, what is under active development, and what is on the longer horizon for the dpp-core library and the dpp-engine infrastructure.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <Section eyebrow="Public roadmap" title="Development status across the two repositories.">
    <p>
      This page mirrors the three-category roadmap presented on the home page and
      adds detail. The categories are deliberately not tied to specific quarters —
      timing on regulatory infrastructure is contingent on too many external
      events (delegated act publication dates, schema-body votes, registry API
      availability) to be promised precisely. The category itself is the
      commitment.
    </p>
    <p>
      The roadmap is reviewed and updated fortnightly. See
      <a href="https://github.com/orgs/odal-node/projects">the public GitHub project board</a>
      for live status on individual items.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="Status" title="The three categories." tone="muted">
    <div class="not-prose">
      <OurRoadmap />
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="How this is maintained" title="What moves a feature between categories.">
    <p>
      A feature moves from <strong>Horizon</strong> to <strong>In build</strong>
      when it enters a sprint and has a named owner. It moves from
      <strong>In build</strong> to <strong>Shipped</strong> when it is in a
      tagged release of the relevant repository, has documentation on
      <a href="https://docs.odal-node.io">docs.odal-node.io</a>, and has an
      automated test exercising it through the running system — "shipped" means
      verified, not merged.
    </p>
    <p>
      Items can move backwards. Discovering that a feature in build needs more
      foundational work is a reasonable outcome of building it; that work moves
      back to the horizon with a note explaining what was learned. Honesty about
      reversals is preferable to silently letting an item drift for six months
      without status.
    </p>
  </Section>
</Base>
